n between central conduction time and ear advantage", "bbox": [252.5, 747.0, 649.3, 762.2]}, {"text": "The relation between the ABR measurements (wave latency, interpeak conduction time) and", "bbox": [252.5, 770.8, 716.4, 783.5]}, {"text": "the ear scores in dichotic listening (under three different attention conditions) is first exam-", "bbox": [252.5, 787.2, 712.3, 799.9]}, {"text": "ined for each ear at each test time. Those pairs that are significantly correlated, p<0.05, are tab-", "bbox": [252.5, 801.5, 727.2, 817.6]}, {"text": "ulated in Table 3. For either ear, the correlation only exists when the dichotic listening task is", "bbox": [252.5, 820.1, 717.0, 832.7]}, {"text": "conducted under the non-forced attention. The correlation is positive at the 1st test time but", "bbox": [252.5, 834.1, 712.6, 849.1]}, {"text": "negative at the 2nd test time. Specifically, the ear score in dichotic listening can relate to the", "bbox": [252.5, 850.5, 706.0, 865.5]}, {"text": "wave latency at peak V, the conduction times at interpeak III-V and interpeak I-V for the right", "bbox": [252.5, 869.3, 725.6, 882.0]}, {"text": "ear, but only the wave latency at peak I for the left ear. Furthermore, the interaural difference", "bbox": [252.5, 885.7, 716.6, 898.4]}, {"text": "PLOS ONE | https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0187672 November 9, 2017 8 / 16", "bbox": [45.5, 946.7, 727.3, 956.8]}]}